                <note rend="inline" type="source">761.9415 Amur River/14: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-07-07T18:00:00+08:00"
                            >July 7, 1937—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 7—8:53 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>205. The following telegram has been received from Harbin: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“July 7, 2 p.m. My telegram No. 10, July 4, noon.</p>
                        <list>
                            <label>1.</label>
                            <item>Local press reports of a new Japanese-Russian clash near Lake
                                Hanka are causing concern.</item>
                            <pb facs="0934" n="927" xml:id="pg_927"/>
                            <label>2.</label>
                            <item>A reliable Manchukuo official states that the Kwantung spokesmen
                                differs widely from Tokyo regarding the settlement of the Amur
                                affair.</item>
                            <label>3.</label>
                            <item>It seems possible that the Kwantung army is, by means of inspired
                                incidents, testing the strength of Soviet military resistance
                                following recent executions in Russia and that the extent to which
                                these incidents may develop will depend upon the stiffness of Soviet
                                resistance.[”]</item>
                        </list>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
